            <Title>CSECS 2020</Title>
            <Text>“Charlotte Smith in the Archive and the Canon.” Canadian Society for Eighteenth-Century Studies. Winnipeg, MB, October 21-24, 2020.

Paper proposals should include a title, a 150-word summary, and a brief biographical note indicating the presenter’s name, email, academic status, and institutional affiliation.

Title: “Playing With the Truth: The Artfully Dishonest Narrator of Tom Jones.”

Abstract: In Henry Fielding’s Tom Jones, the flamboyantly omnipresent narrator frequently draws attention to his role in arranging and presenting his textual evidence for the reader. I examine one phrase, “to say the truth,” which the narrator uses eighty-two times across the text to introduce new information — not all of which might really be considered “the truth.” These moments in the text challenge the assumption that anything said by a narrator of a novel must be definition constitute that novel’s reality, and support existing readings which see the novel as Fielding’s lesson in epistemology. However, looking more closely at how and when Fielding’s narrator plays with the truth, I argue that these moments are in fact anti-didactic, intended to prevent the reader from looking too closely at the novel’s machinery.

Bio: Lawrence Evalyn (lawrence.evalyn@mail.utoronto.ca), Ph.D. Candidate in English at the University of Toronto.

Please send your proposals to the following email address: csecs-scedhs-2020@uwinnipeg.ca.</Text>
